Here's the `README.md` — save it to the root of your project:

```markdown
# 🎰 Pinball

AI-generated pinball strategy guides, built with [Jekyll](https://jekyllrb.com/)
and the [Minima](https://github.com/jekyll/minima) theme. Hosted on GitHub Pages at
[sbeckeriv.github.io/collective_plans](https://sbeckeriv.github.io/collective_plans/).

---

## Prerequisites

You'll need the following installed before getting started:

- **Ruby** (version 3.3.0 — pinned via `.ruby-version`)
- **RubyGems**
- **Git**

### Installing Ruby

#### macOS

macOS ships with an old system Ruby. Use [Homebrew](https://brew.sh/) instead:

```bash
brew install ruby
```

Then add Ruby to your PATH (add this to your `~/.zshrc` or `~/.bashrc`):

```bash
export PATH="/opt/homebrew/opt/ruby/bin:$PATH"
```

#### Ubuntu / Debian

```bash
sudo apt-get install ruby-full build-essential
```

Then configure a local gem directory to avoid needing `sudo`:

```bash
echo '# Install Ruby Gems to ~/gems' >> ~/.bashrc
echo 'export GEM_HOME="$HOME/gems"' >> ~/.bashrc
echo 'export PATH="$HOME/gems/bin:$PATH"' >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc
```

#### Windows

Use [RubyInstaller](https://rubyinstaller.org/). Download and run the
installer with the **MSYS2 toolchain** option checked. Alternatively, use
[WSL](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/) and follow the
Ubuntu instructions above.

---

## Installing Dependencies

Once Ruby is set up, install the project's gems via Bundler:

```bash
cd pinball-db
bundle install
```

This reads the `Gemfile` and installs everything needed, including:

- `jekyll` — the static site generator
- `minima` — the theme
- `jekyll-paginate-v2` — pagination support for the machine listing
- `jekyll-seo-tag` — SEO meta tags
- `jekyll-sitemap` — auto-generated sitemap

---

## Previewing Locally

Start the local development server:

```bash
bundle exec jekyll serve --baseurl ""
```

Then open your browser and visit:

```
http://localhost:4000
```

Note: The `--baseurl ""` flag is needed because the production site uses `/collective_plans` as the baseurl.

The site will **automatically rebuild** whenever you save changes to any file.

### Useful flags

| Flag           | Description                           |
| -------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| `--livereload` | Auto-refreshes the browser on changes |
| `--drafts`     | Includes draft posts in the build     |
| `--port 5000`  | Run on a different port               |

Example with live reload:

```bash
bundle exec jekyll serve --livereload
```

---

## Adding Machines

Each pinball machine is a Markdown file inside the `_pinball/` folder.
Copy the template below and save it as `_pinball/your-machine-name.md`:

```yaml
---
title: "Machine Title"
manufacturer: Stern
year: 2001
designer: Steve Ritchie
artist: ""
type: DMD              # EM | Solid State | DMD | LCD
theme: Movies
players: 4
ipdb_id: 123           # Find at https://www.ipdb.org
features:
  - multiball
  - ramps
image: /assets/images/pinball/your-machine.jpg
---

Write a description of the machine here in plain Markdown.
```

Place any cover images in `assets/images/pinball/`. Images should be **256×256px** for consistency across the site.

---

## Deploying to GitHub Pages

> **Why GitHub Actions?** The `jekyll-paginate-v2` plugin is not on GitHub's
> approved plugin list, so the default Pages build process won't work. Instead,
> we use a GitHub Actions workflow to build the site and deploy the output.
> This is already set up in `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`.

### Step 1 — Create a GitHub repository

1. Go to [github.com/new](https://github.com/new)
2. Name your repository (e.g. `pinball-db`)
3. Set it to **Public** (required for free GitHub Pages)
4. Do **not** initialise with a README (you already have one)

### Step 2 — Push your code

```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO.git
git push -u origin main
```

### Step 3 — Enable GitHub Pages

1. Go to your repository on GitHub
2. Click **Settings** → **Pages** (in the left sidebar)
3. Under **Build and deployment**, set Source to **GitHub Actions**

### Step 4 — Verify the deployment

GitHub Actions will automatically build and deploy your site on every push
to `main`. You can watch the progress under the **Actions** tab of your repo.

Once deployed, your site will be live at:

```
https://YOUR_USERNAME.github.io/YOUR_REPO/
```

### Subsequent deploys

Every time you push changes to `main`, the site rebuilds and deploys
automatically — no manual steps needed.

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Add 10 new machines"
git push
```

