## Project Structure

```
collective_plans/
├── _pinball/                  # One .md file per machine
├── _layouts/
│   └── machine.html           # Individual machine page template
├── _includes/
│   ├── footer.html            # Custom footer with GitHub link
│   └── head.html              # Custom <head>: PWA meta, AI signals, service worker registration
├── _sass/
│   └── custom.scss            # Custom styles (grid, filters, images)
├── assets/
│   ├── main.scss              # SCSS entry point (imports minima + custom)
│   └── images/pinball/        # Machine cover art (256×256px)
├── .github/workflows/
│   └── deploy.yml             # GitHub Actions build & deploy
├── _config.yml                # Jekyll configuration
├── .ruby-version              # Ruby version (3.3.0)
├── Gemfile                    # Ruby dependencies
├── index.md                   # Homepage with machine grid
├── pinball.html               # Filterable machine listing
├── manifest.json              # PWA manifest (name, icons, display mode)
└── sw.js                      # Service worker (offline caching)
```

---

## PWA & Offline Support

The site is a Progressive Web App (PWA). Visitors can install it to their home screen and read guides offline — useful at arcades with poor signal.

### Installing on Android

1. Open the site in Chrome
2. Visit a couple of pages (Chrome requires some engagement before offering the prompt)
3. Tap the **"Add to Home Screen"** banner, or open Chrome's menu → **Install app**

The app launches in standalone mode (no browser chrome) and any guide page you've previously visited will load offline.

### Installing on iOS

1. Open the site in Safari
2. Tap the Share button → **Add to Home Screen**

### How caching works

| Content type | Strategy |
| ------------ | -------- |
| Guide pages (HTML) | Network-first, cache fallback — fresh when online, readable offline |
| Images | Cache-first — pinball images don't change |
| CSS / JS | Cache-first |
| Shell (homepage, CSS, manifest, icon) | Pre-cached on install |

### Bumping the cache version

When you do a significant content push, update the version string at the top of `sw.js`:

```js
// sw.js
const CACHE = 'pinball-v1'; // ← change to pinball-v2, pinball-v3, etc.
```

The service worker's `activate` handler automatically deletes the old cache version on the user's next visit, so they pick up the new content.

### AI content signals

All guides include two meta tags that signal AI-generated content to crawlers:

```html
<meta name="ai-generated" content="true">
<meta name="robots" content="noai, noimageai">
```

These are controlled by the `ai_generated: true` field in each guide's frontmatter. Adding that field to any page opts it into the signals; omitting it leaves the page untagged.

---

## Troubleshooting

**`bundle: command not found`**
→ Run `gem install bundler` first.

**`Permission denied` errors when running `gem install`**
→ Make sure you followed the local gem directory setup above — avoid using `sudo gem install`.

**Changes not showing up locally**
→ Stop the server (`Ctrl+C`) and restart with `bundle exec jekyll serve`.

**GitHub Actions failing**
→ Click the **Actions** tab in your repo and open the failing workflow run to read the error log.

